WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.500
These pictures are tiny — book-page

00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:05.020
woodcuts you could hold in your hand, not

00:00:05.020 --> 00:00:07.700
the vast frescoes that once sprawled

00:00:07.700 --> 00:00:09.640
across the walls of medieval churchyards.

00:00:10.100 --> 00:00:12.280
For centuries they've been filed under a

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:15.300
calm, dutiful label: a memento mori, a

00:00:15.300 --> 00:00:17.340
polite reminder that everyone, sooner or

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:18.460
later, must die.

00:00:18.980 --> 00:00:21.120
And yet, hidden inside the sequence, there

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:23.940
is a single image that quietly turns the

00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:26.720
whole thing inside out — that takes what

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:29.160
looks like a sermon and reveals something

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:30.420
far closer to a weapon.
